    'cultural_cristo_desc':
        'The Mosque of Cristo de la Luz, built in 999 AD, is one of Toledo\'s most emblematic monuments. This small mosque of late Caliphal style represents a unique testimony of Islamic architecture in the city. Its original structure remains practically intact, including horseshoe arches and later Mud√©jar decoration. Declared a Site of Cultural Interest, it offers guided tours that narrate its fascinating history of transformation from mosque to Christian church.',
    'cultural_santacruz_desc':
        'The Santa Cruz Museum, located in a magnificent 16th-century Renaissance hospital, houses an exceptional collection of Toledo art and archaeology. Its rooms display masterpieces by El Greco, Visigothic art, Talavera ceramics, and an important collection of Flemish tapestries. The building itself is an architectural gem with its impressive Plateresque staircase and Renaissance cloister. It is considered one of the most important museums in Castilla-La Mancha.',
    'cultural_sinagoga_desc':
        'The Synagogue of Santa Mar√≠a la Blanca, built in the 12th century, is an exceptional example of Toledo Mud√©jar architecture. Its five naves separated by horseshoe arches on octagonal columns create a unique space that reflects the coexistence of three cultures. Although transformed into a Christian church in the 15th century, it preserves its original structure and Islamic geometric decoration. It is considered the oldest standing synagogue in Europe.',
    'cultural_greco_desc':
        'The El Greco Museum pays tribute to the brilliant Cretan painter who made Toledo his home during his final years. The collection includes masterpieces such as "View and Plan of Toledo" and "The Tears of Saint Peter," along with personal objects and documents that illustrate the artist\'s life. The museum occupies two connected historic buildings: the Villena Palace and a 16th-century house that recreates the domestic atmosphere of the painter\'s era.',
    'cultural_tornerias_desc':
        'The Mosque of Las Torner√≠as, a small 11th-century gem, is one of Toledo\'s best-preserved Islamic constructions. Its architecture reflects the Taifa period, with unique decorative elements including Kufic inscriptions and original plasterwork. Located in the heart of the historic center, it allows appreciation of Andalusi construction techniques and their later Christian adaptation. It is an exceptional testimony of medieval Islamic Toledo.',
    'cultural_sefardi_desc':
        'The Sephardic Museum, located in the Synagogue del Tr√°nsito (14th century), tells the rich history of the Jewish community in Spain. Its collections include ritual objects, Hebrew manuscripts, historical documents, and architectural elements that illustrate eight centuries of Sephardic presence. The synagogue itself is a masterpiece of Jewish Mud√©jar art, with polychrome plasterwork and Hebrew inscriptions that make it a unique space in the world.',
    'ruta_senda_ecologica_desc':
        'Trail along the Tagus River, ideal for family walks.',
    'ruta_piedra_rey_moro_desc':
        'Circular route with legends and views of the Tagus River.',
    'ruta_montes_toledo_desc':
        'Excursion through the mountains with native flora and fauna.',
    'cultural_tourism_desc':
        'Discover the historical and monumental richness of Toledo through its museums, churches, and synagogues.',
    'gastronomy_desc':
        'Enjoy the best Toledo cuisine in typical restaurants and bars of the city.',
    'nature_desc':
        'Explore unique routes and natural landscapes around Toledo.',
    'nightlife_desc':
        'Experience Toledo\'s nightlife with tours, pubs, nightclubs, and cultural activities.',
    'free_tour_desc':
        'Embark on a unique experience with our specialized free tours that will reveal the best-kept secrets of Toledo through thematic routes designed by experts in medieval history, Mud√©jar art, and UNESCO heritage. Discover the fascinating history of the Imperial City guided by certified local expert guides who will take you on a comprehensive tour of the most emblematic monuments: from the majestic Primate Cathedral with its unique Gothic treasures and the famous Transparente by Narciso Tom√©, to the mysterious cobblestone alleys of the Jewish quarter with its Mud√©jar synagogues of Santa Mar√≠a la Blanca and El Tr√°nsito, passing through the imposing imperial Alc√°zar that dominates the city, the ancient mosques of Cristo de la Luz (999 AD) and Las Torner√≠as converted into churches after the Reconquest, and strategic viewpoints offering spectacular panoramic views of the Tagus meander and the surrounding landscape of the Toledo Mountains. Our specialized guides, trained in local history and urban legends, will reveal fascinating historical curiosities, anecdotes about El Greco and his golden era in Toledo, secrets of medieval architecture, hidden symbolism in religious monuments, and stories about the famous School of Translators that you won\'t find in any conventional tourist guide. You\'ll understand why Toledo was called the "City of Three Cultures" and how the peaceful medieval coexistence between Christians, Muslims, and Jews for more than eight centuries created an absolutely unique artistic, architectural, and cultural heritage in the world, recognized by UNESCO as a World Heritage Site.',
    'toledo_guides': 'Toledo Guides',
    'toledo_guides_desc':
        'Discover Toledo with our specialized guides offering perfectly optimized itineraries to explore the Imperial City according to your interests and available time. Our expert guides, developed by local historians and UNESCO heritage specialists, include thematic routes to discover the most emblematic monuments such as the Gothic Primate Cathedral, the imperial Alc√°zar, the Mud√©jar synagogues of the Jewish quarter, and the historic mosques converted into churches. Each guide incorporates detailed historical information about the coexistence of the three cultures, gastronomic recommendations to taste authentic specialties like conventual marzipan and traditional carcamusas, interactive maps with optimized routes that avoid crowds, updated schedules of monuments and museums, and practical advice about the best panoramic viewpoints of the Tagus meander. The guides are designed for different visitor profiles: from intensive one-day tours to relaxed weekend routes, including family options and specialized routes focused on art, gastronomy, nature, and medieval architecture.',

    // Free Tour Content
    'free_tour_intro_title':
        'Free Tours de Toledo: Descubre la Ciudad Imperial sin Coste',
    'free_tour_intro_text':
        'Los Free Tours de Toledo representan una oportunidad √∫nica para conocer en profundidad la rica historia de la Ciudad Imperial de la mano de gu√≠as especializados y sin coste fijo. Estos recorridos gratuitos, basados en el sistema de propinas voluntarias, han revolucionado el turismo cultural permitiendo el acceso democr√°tico al patrimonio hist√≥rico de Toledo. Los gu√≠as, expertos en historia local, arte y leyendas toledanas, comparten su pasi√≥n por la ciudad ofreciendo explicaciones detalladas, an√©cdotas hist√≥ricas y contexto cultural que enriquece enormemente la visita. La filosof√≠a de los Free Tours se basa en la calidad del servicio y la satisfacci√≥n del visitante, creando una experiencia aut√©ntica y personalizada.',
    'free_tour_benefits_title': 'Ventajas de los Free Tours',
    'free_tour_benefits_text':
        'Los Free Tours ofrecen m√∫ltiples ventajas para el visitante: flexibilidad econ√≥mica al pagar seg√∫n la satisfacci√≥n, grupos reducidos que permiten atenci√≥n personalizada, gu√≠as apasionados que transmiten amor por la ciudad, rutas optimizadas que cubren los puntos m√°s importantes en tiempo limitado, y la posibilidad de hacer preguntas espec√≠ficas sobre historia, cultura o recomendaciones locales. Adem√°s, muchos tours incluyen acceso a miradores exclusivos, explicaciones sobre simbolog√≠as ocultas en monumentos, y consejos pr√°cticos para aprovechar al m√°ximo la estancia en Toledo. La interacci√≥n directa con gu√≠as locales proporciona una perspectiva aut√©ntica que dif√≠cilmente se obtiene en visitas autoguiadas.',

    'guide_one_day_title': 'What to see in Toledo in one day?',
    'guide_one_day_summary':
        'Discover the perfectly optimized itinerary to explore the essentials of Toledo in one complete day. This specialized guide will take you through the must-see monuments of the Imperial City, including the Primate Cathedral with its unique Gothic treasures, the majestic Alc√°zar dominating the city, the Mud√©jar synagogues of Santa Mar√≠a la Blanca and El Tr√°nsito that testify to the coexistence of the three cultures, and the historic mosques of Cristo de la Luz and Las Torner√≠as. Includes gastronomic recommendations to taste authentic Toledo marzipan and famous carcamusas in centenary taverns, as well as the best viewpoints to contemplate panoramic views of the Tagus meander and optimized routes that will allow you to make the most of your time exploring more than 2000 years of history in the historic center declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site.',
    'guide_gastronomy_title': 'History of Toledo Gastronomy',
    'guide_gastronomy_summary':
        'Immerse yourself in a fascinating culinary journey that discovers the millenary origins and historical evolution of traditional Toledo gastronomy. Explore how the coexistence of the three cultures - Christian, Muslim and Jewish - created a unique gastronomic fusion that endures to this day. Discover the secrets of Toledo marzipan made since the 11th century in historic convents with recipes jealously guarded by generations of Clarist nuns, the history of carcamusas born in 19th-century taverns, and the tradition of "Toledo-style" stewed partridge with chocolate, a technique inherited from 17th-century convent cuisine. Learn about the origins of artisanal cheeses from Los Montes de Toledo, the wine-making tradition with Denomination of Origin, and how medieval commercial exchanges enriched the Toledo pantry with oriental spices like La Mancha saffron, considered the finest in the world.',
    'guide_cultures_title': 'The Three Cultures in Toledo',
    'guide_cultures_summary':
        'Explore in depth the exceptional legacy of the historical coexistence between Christians, Muslims and Jews that turned Toledo into a unique model of medieval tolerance in Europe. Discover the history of the famous "School of Translators of Toledo" which during the 12th and 13th centuries became the main center of cultural and intellectual exchange in the West, where scholars of the three religions collaborated to translate and transmit classical Greco-Latin knowledge and oriental sciences. Learn about the flourishing of the Toledo Jewish community, one of the most important in the Iberian Peninsula with up to 12 synagogues functioning simultaneously, the splendor of Mud√©jar architecture that fuses Christian and Islamic elements, and how this unique cultural syncretism produced architectural, artistic and literary masterpieces that have endured more than a thousand years and constitute today an exceptional testimony declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site.',
    'guide_seasons_title': 'Seasonal Routes',
    'guide_seasons_summary':
        'Discover the best times of year to visit Toledo and the unique activities each season offers. Toledo spring (March-May) transforms the city into a Mediterranean garden where almond, orange and rose trees bloom in historic courtyards, while mild temperatures invite long walks along medieval walls and hiking routes through the Toledo Mountains. Summer (June-August) offers the "Toledo Music Festival" with concerts in Renaissance courtyards, nighttime light and sound shows at the Cathedral, and the famous "Toledo Nights" with special visits to illuminated monuments. Autumn (September-November) is ideal for gastronomy with hunting season, gastronomic festivals, harvests in local wineries and mycological routes through centenary dehesas. Winter (December-February) reveals the most intimate Toledo with Christmas markets in Plaza de Zocodover, living nativity scenes in historic churches, and the special magic of occasional snow that transforms the medieval skyline into a fairy-tale postcard.',
